This is a master-chef–level Filipino garlic fried rice (sinangag). It is austere, technique-driven, and optimized for aroma, texture, and restraint. The defining characteristic is toasted garlic oil, not soy sauce or excess seasoning.

Ingredients (serves 2–3):
• 3 cups cooked day-old jasmine rice, cold and fully dried
• 12–16 cloves garlic, finely minced (do not use a press)
• 4–5 tablespoons neutral oil (rice bran or peanut preferred)
• 1–1½ teaspoons kosher salt, adjusted to taste
• Optional: 1 teaspoon chicken fat or pork fat for depth
• Optional finishing: flaky salt, finely sliced scallions

Preparation principles:
The rice must be cold, dry, and separated by hand before cooking. Moist or freshly cooked rice will steam and fail. Garlic is cooked gently first; the rice is fried second. This sequencing is non-negotiable.

Method:
	1.	Place a cold wok or wide skillet over low heat. Add oil (and optional animal fat).
	2.	Add garlic and cook slowly, stirring constantly. You are extracting aroma and creating pale golden chips, not browning aggressively. This should take 4–6 minutes.
	3.	When garlic is lightly golden and intensely fragrant, remove half of it with a slotted spoon and reserve. Keep the garlic oil in the pan.
	4.	Increase heat to medium-high. Add rice, spreading it out. Do not stir for 30–45 seconds to allow surface dehydration.
	5.	Toss decisively, breaking clumps by pressing—not mashing—with the spatula.
	6.	Season with salt in two stages, tasting as you go. The rice should be savory but clean.
	7.	Continue frying 3–5 minutes until grains are hot, dry, and lightly blistered.
	8.	Return reserved garlic, toss once, and immediately remove from heat.

Finish and serve:
Taste, correct with a pinch of flaky salt if needed, and optionally garnish with scallions. Serve plain or alongside eggs, longganisa, tocino, tapa, or grilled seafood.